[The 1st published report of bluetongue virus (BTV) infection in South America was a case from Brazil in 1978. Subsequently, serological surveys have determined that the infection is widespread in sheep, cattle, goats, and water buffalo but generally without clinical signs.

Brocket deer (_Mazama_ spp.) are neotropical cervids of small to medium size. Out of the 10 species of _Mazama_, the pigmy brocket (_Mazama nana_) is the smallest (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pygmy_brocket#/media/File:Mazama_nana.jpg).

Serosurveys of free-ranging wild deer in South America suggest that BTV circulates in their populations. - Mod.PMB

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3948490,10423.]
